{"parentUuid":"67f67f76-a167-4372-80c6-d41b41cddbb0","isSidechain":false,"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Base directory for this skill: /Users/ck/.claude/skills/db-backup\n\n# Database Backup\n\nBackup remote PostgreSQL databases running in Docker containers via SSH, download the dump locally, and restore to a local PostgreSQL instance.\n\n## Config: `db-backup.yml`\n\nThe skill reads `db-backup.yml` from the project root. If the file does not exist, **help the user create one** by asking for the required values.\n\n### Schema\n\n```yaml\nenvironments:\n  <env_name>:                # e.g. test, prod, staging\n    ssh_host: <string>       # SSH alias or host (must be in ~/.ssh/config)\n    container: <string>      # Docker container running PostgreSQL\n    db_name: <string>        # Database name inside the container\n    db_user: <string>        # PostgreSQL user\n    db_password: <string>    # PostgreSQL password (optional — prompts if missing)\n    confirm: <bool>          # If true, ask user for explicit confirmation before running (default: false)\n\nlocal:\n  host: 127.0.0.1\n  port: 5432\n  user: postgres\n  password: postgres\n\nbackup_dir: ~/Documents/DB_Backups   # Local directory for dump files\n```\n\n### Creating Config When Missing\n\nIf `db-backup.yml` is not found in the project root, ask the user:\n\n1. Which environments to configure (e.g. test, prod)\n2. For each environment: SSH host, container name, db name, db user, db password\n3. Whether the environment needs confirmation before backup (recommend `true` for prod)\n4. Local PostgreSQL connection details\n5. Local backup directory path\n\nWrite the file and confirm with the user before proceeding.\n\n## Backup Procedure\n\n### Step 0: Read config\n\n```bash\n# Parse db-backup.yml for the requested environment\n# Abort if environment not found\n```\n\n### Step 1: Confirm (if required)\n\nIf `confirm: true` for the environment, ask the user:\n> \"About to backup **{env_name}** ({ssh_host}:{db_name}). This is a READ-ONLY operation. Proceed?\"\n\nDo NOT proceed without explicit confirmation for environments with `confirm: true`.\n\n### Step 2: Dump inside container\n\n```bash\nDATE=$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S)\nDUMP_FILE={db_name}_dump_${DATE}.dump\n\nssh {ssh_host} \"docker exec -e PGPASSWORD={db_password} {container} pg_dump -U {db_user} -F c -b -d {db_name} -f /tmp/$DUMP_FILE\"\n```\n\n### Step 3: Copy dump out of container\n\n```bash\nssh {ssh_host} \"docker cp {container}:/tmp/$DUMP_FILE /tmp/$DUMP_FILE\"\n```\n\n### Step 4: Clean up container temp file\n\n```bash\nssh {ssh_host} \"docker exec {container} rm -f /tmp/$DUMP_FILE\"\n```\n\n### Step 5: Download to local machine\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p {backup_dir}\nscp {ssh_host}:/tmp/$DUMP_FILE {backup_dir}/$DUMP_FILE\n```\n\n### Step 6: Clean up server temp file\n\n```bash\nssh {ssh_host} \"rm -f /tmp/$DUMP_FILE\"\n```\n\n### Step 7: Restore to local PostgreSQL\n\n```bash\nBACKUP_DB={db_name}_backup_${DATE}\n\nPGPASSWORD={local.password} createdb -h {local.host} -p {local.port} -U {local.user} $BACKUP_DB\n\nPGPASSWORD={local.password} pg_restore -h {local.host} -p {local.port} -U {local.user} -d $BACKUP_DB {backup_dir}/$DUMP_FILE\n```\n\n### Step 8: Report\n\nPrint summary:\n- Environment backed up\n- Dump file path: `{backup_dir}/$DUMP_FILE`\n- Local database name: `$BACKUP_DB`\n- Timestamp\n\n## Invocation\n\nThe user may say:\n- \"backup the test database\"\n- \"backup prod db\"\n- \"backup db before migration\"\n- `/backup-db test`\n- `/backup-db prod`\n\nParse the environment name from the request. If ambiguous, ask which environment.\n\n## Rules\n\n1. **Read-only on remote** — only `pg_dump`, `docker cp`, and cleanup of temp files. Never write data to remote databases.\n2. **Confirm prod** — always require confirmation for environments with `confirm: true`.\n3. **Clean up** — always remove temp dump files from both the container and the server host after download.\n4. **Never store passwords in shell history** — use `-e PGPASSWORD=` with `docker exec`, not shell export.\n5. **Fail fast** — if any step fails, stop immediately and report which step failed. Do not continue to cleanup if the dump itself failed.\n6. **Ensure backup_dir exists** — create it with `mkdir -p` before downloading.\n\n## Common Issues\n\n| Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n|---------|-------|-----|\n| `ssh: Could not resolve hostname` | SSH alias not in ~/.ssh/config | Check `~/.ssh/config` for the host alias |\n| `Error: No such container` | Wrong container name in config | Run `ssh {host} \"docker ps --format '{{.Names}}\"` to find correct name |\n| `pg_dump: connection refused` | PostgreSQL not running in container | Check `ssh {host} \"docker logs {container} --tail 20\"` |\n| `createdb: database already exists` | Duplicate timestamp (very rare) | Wait a second and retry, or manually specify a different name |\n| `pg_restore: errors` | Version mismatch between remote and local pg | Check PostgreSQL versions; use matching `pg_restore` version |\n\n\nARGUMENTS: test"}]},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"a7d244cb-6382-4e22-9ea9-86adff19814e","timestamp":"2026-03-30T07:30:40.446Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"/Users/ck/Git/matrix/devtrack","sessionId":"72cc991e-f5f4-4891-b86f-fb4ef937e24d","version":"2.1.85","gitBranch":"main"}
